MISRAC2012-RULE_1_3-a.example_violation:
This rule can detect a variety of situations where division
by zero may occur. Below are a few examples that will trigger a
violation.

static int zeroMethod()
{
    return 0;
}

static void assignmentRemainderOfMethodResult()
{
    int a = 5;
    a %= zeroMethod(); // VIOLATION
}

static void assignRemainderOfVar()
{
    int a = 5;
    int b = 0;
    a %= b; // VIOLATION
}

MISRAC2012-RULE_1_3-a.example_repair:
Whenever there is a chance that zero may occur in a denominator,
it is necessary to use additional methods to ensure that the denominator
is not zero.

static int zeroMethod()
{
    return 0;
}

static void assignmentRemainderOfMethodResult()
{
    int a = 5;
    int b = zeroMethod();
    if (b != 0) {
        a %= b; // NO VIOLATION
    }
}

static void assignRemainderOfVar()
{
    int a = 5;
    int b = 0;
    if (b != 0) {
        a %= b; // NO VIOLATION
    }
}

MISRAC2012-RULE_1_3-b.example_violation:
int i;
    char c[100];
Here, "i" and "c" are non-initialized.

For the purpose of this rule, an object is partially-initialized when:
 - it is a class/struct object with some, but not all, initialized non-static members, or
 - it is an array with some initialized elements, but the analyzer cannot deduce that all elements are initialized
Example:
    struct S {
       int a, b, c;
    };
    S s;
    s.b = 1;
Here, "s" is partially-initialized, because it contains non-initialized members "s.a" and "s.c".

For the purpose of this rule, an element of an array is potentially-initialized when
the array contains at least one initialized element, but the analyzer cannot deduce if this is the same element.
Example:
    char buf[100];
    buf[index] = 0;
    int array[10];
    array[0] = 0;
Here, "buf[42]" is a potentially-initialized element of an array if the analyzer cannot prove that "index == 42".
Also, "array[index]" is a potentially-initialized element of an array if the analyzer cannot prove that "index == 0".

MISRAC2012-RULE_1_3-b.example_repair:
Always initialize a variable before its use.

struct S {
    int a;
    const char* b;
    int c;
};

int test01(int a)
{
    int i = 1;
    return a + i; // NO VIOLATION
}

int test02(int a)
{
    int tab[2];
    tab[0] = 1;
    tab[1] = 1;
    return tab[1]; // NO VIOLATION
}

int test03()
{
    struct S s = { 1, "ABC", 1 };
    return s.c; // NO VIOLATION
}

void test04()
{
    struct S s1;
    s1.a = 1;
    s1.b = "ABC";
    s1.c = 1;
    struct S s2 = s1; // NO VIOLATION
}

